00:16:23,844 --> 00:16:31,266
[SPEAKER_07]: All right, then the motion is carried to move the vote on the co-chairs to January.

204
00:16:31,927 --> 00:16:33,727
[SPEAKER_07]: The meeting will occur on January 8th.

205
00:16:35,728 --> 00:16:37,289
[SPEAKER_07]: We are going to meet on a holiday.

206
00:16:38,449 --> 00:16:43,131
[SPEAKER_00]: Bob, this is a great point for me to actually insert an administrative thing that I hadn't

207
00:16:45,773 --> 00:16:49,201
[SPEAKER_00]: While you were saying this, I realized that this is a great time to mention it.

208
00:16:49,301 --> 00:16:54,351
[SPEAKER_00]: Since everybody is here, Brenda, I'll check in with the two members who are not here.

209
00:16:55,679 --> 00:17:12,830
[SPEAKER_00]: tomorrow, people may not be aware that if for some reason you can't make a meeting, even if it's at the very last minute, sending an email to Brenda and Bob or a text if you have their information or whatever, some message is extremely helpful.

210
00:17:13,270 --> 00:17:20,755
[SPEAKER_00]: If you know in advance you can't make a meeting, letting us know in advance, because we have had times when it's really hard to make quorum with this group.

211
00:17:21,315 --> 00:17:25,098
[SPEAKER_00]: And if we know that it looks like half the people can't come,

212
00:17:25,638 --> 00:17:29,099
[SPEAKER_00]: then we won't waste everybody else's time and we'll figure something else out.

213
00:17:29,840 --> 00:17:36,902
[SPEAKER_00]: But I just wanted to mention that, that not everybody may realize that sending, letting Brenda and Bob know if you're not coming.

214
00:17:37,022 --> 00:17:40,123
[SPEAKER_00]: It used to be me, but I'm kind of passing the torch to Brenda.

215
00:17:42,044 --> 00:17:50,687
[SPEAKER_00]: And if for some reason you do message me for whatever reason, or like you can text me, but you can't text Brenda, I'll pass the message along.

216
00:17:51,088 --> 00:17:52,048
[SPEAKER_00]: So thanks.

217
00:17:54,945 --> 00:18:10,817
[SPEAKER_07]: We talked last month about having occasional in-person meetings, and I don't know if we need to do that on January 8th, but it could be considered.

218
00:18:11,897 --> 00:18:13,479
[SPEAKER_07]: I'll open the floor for discussion.

219
00:18:13,499 --> 00:18:22,185
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we were thinking about once a quarter or so, but I'll open the floor for discussion on frequency of in-person meetings versus Zoom.

220
00:18:28,531 --> 00:18:29,652
[SPEAKER_05]: I think it's a good idea.

221
00:18:31,834 --> 00:18:33,075
[SPEAKER_07]: To have an in-person meeting.

222
00:18:34,056 --> 00:18:42,102
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes, I think it's a good idea to occasionally, you know, find out if we're all real or not.

223
00:18:45,745 --> 00:18:46,105
[SPEAKER_05]: Check.

224
00:18:49,468 --> 00:18:49,828
[SPEAKER_12]: Okay.

225
00:18:50,678 --> 00:18:57,681
[SPEAKER_12]: I will also agree that occasional in-person meetings are certainly good.

226
00:18:57,701 --> 00:19:07,925
[SPEAKER_12]: I definitely appreciate the opportunity to participate in these meetings remotely, though, for a number of reasons.

227
00:19:08,025 --> 00:19:12,767
[SPEAKER_12]: This is very convenient and effective from my perspective.

228
00:19:13,788 --> 00:19:19,190
[SPEAKER_12]: But I do also enjoy the opportunity to actually see people in real life.

