445
00:37:21,492 --> 00:37:31,036
[SPEAKER_09]: All you have to do is refer in the ordinance to EOEEA's prohibited plant list.

446
00:37:31,996 --> 00:37:32,116
[SPEAKER_09]: And

447
00:37:34,332 --> 00:37:37,614
[SPEAKER_09]: You know, I mean, you could end up in quite a pickle.

448
00:37:37,674 --> 00:37:44,779
[SPEAKER_09]: Norway maples are really long-lived, and there are many that exceed 75 years, and we might want them out of there.

449
00:37:46,841 --> 00:37:50,103
[SPEAKER_09]: You know, tree of heaven and black locust can grow quite large, too.

450
00:37:50,143 --> 00:37:52,304
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm not sure that they live to 75 years.

451
00:37:54,546 --> 00:38:03,272
[SPEAKER_09]: But I think that we really need to exclude those from the definitions.

452
00:38:04,902 --> 00:38:08,584
[SPEAKER_09]: My comments on the private tree ordinance were more extensive.

453
00:38:13,005 --> 00:38:29,452
[SPEAKER_09]: Again, there's the issue of invasive and noxious species with a little bit more particularity, because there you're talking about DBH of 10 inches or greater, and lots of invasive trees could have a DBH of 10 inches or greater.

454
00:38:33,786 --> 00:38:43,568
[SPEAKER_09]: Their second comment was regarding mitigation and tree replacement.

455
00:38:44,169 --> 00:39:02,373
[SPEAKER_09]: I think I talked about this a little bit last time, but the ordinance calls for replacing a 10 to 15 inch tree with two trees of three inch caliber, a 15 to 30 inch tree with three trees of three inch caliber,

456
00:39:05,368 --> 00:39:17,258
[SPEAKER_09]: And a 30-inch or more tree with four trees of three-inch caliber, which are, I mean, I'm not even sure why bother.

457
00:39:17,398 --> 00:39:18,879
[SPEAKER_09]: That's so lax.

458
00:39:19,880 --> 00:39:31,750
[SPEAKER_09]: In terms of ecosystem services, even the previous, this is worse than the previous version of looking at total diameter, but

459
00:39:32,647 --> 00:39:42,635
[SPEAKER_09]: the idea that two, three-inch trees could replace the ecosystem services of a 12-inch tree is kind of ridiculous.

460
00:39:43,696 --> 00:39:47,359
[SPEAKER_09]: And that's the just, you know, that's the purpose of this ordinance, right?

461
00:39:47,379 --> 00:39:51,062
[SPEAKER_09]: That's what's laid out as the purpose is these ecosystem services.

462
00:39:53,043 --> 00:39:57,267
[SPEAKER_09]: You, a closer approximation of

463
00:39:59,391 --> 00:40:04,673
[SPEAKER_09]: of reaching equivalent ecosystem services would be the area of a cross section.

464
00:40:05,594 --> 00:40:12,496
[SPEAKER_09]: So the number of three-inch trees to replace a 12-inch tree would be around 16.

465
00:40:13,817 --> 00:40:19,279
[SPEAKER_09]: And the number of three-inch trees to replace a 24-inch tree would be about 24.

466
00:40:21,400 --> 00:40:26,022
[SPEAKER_09]: And the number of three-inch trees to replace a 30-inch tree would be about 100.

467
00:40:28,561 --> 00:40:45,574
[SPEAKER_09]: That's when you begin to have, that's when you have equivalent mitigation effects in terms of hydrological impacts and everything else because it's not the diameter, it's the total size of the tree.

468
00:40:45,614 --> 00:40:48,797
[SPEAKER_09]: How much shade is it providing?

469
00:40:48,837 --> 00:40:50,258
[SPEAKER_09]: How much water is it drawing?

470
00:40:52,120 --> 00:40:55,963
[SPEAKER_09]: How much of a root system is there to hold the soil in place?

471
00:40:56,635 --> 00:41:01,778
[SPEAKER_09]: You know, three-inch trees don't do it, not compared to a 30-inch tree.

472
00:41:03,398 --> 00:41:09,181
[SPEAKER_09]: So, I mean, you might not want to stipulate the equivalent.

473
00:41:09,261 --> 00:41:20,467
[SPEAKER_09]: It might be kind of onerous to say that you need 100 to replace a 30-inch tree with 100 trees, because there might not be a place to put 100 trees.

474
00:41:24,925 --> 00:41:29,806
[SPEAKER_09]: but for trees is really extremely lax.

