01:10:01,622 --> 01:10:11,290
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's both in the emergencies, but it's like, you know, you're building a house, you need to be able to remove the tree to put the house on the lot.

756
01:10:11,790 --> 01:10:13,231
[SPEAKER_00]: and then plant some other trees.

757
01:10:14,571 --> 01:10:27,537
[SPEAKER_00]: For example, the housing authority needs to redevelop their lot, and they're happy to plant new trees, but they need to be able to remove trees in order to lay out this in a way that makes sense.

758
01:10:28,538 --> 01:10:40,188
[SPEAKER_00]: And so he was looking for mechanisms whereby he could do math, he could look at plans, and he could check things off and say, here is the math.

759
01:10:40,789 --> 01:10:42,290
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, now you can go.

760
01:10:42,310 --> 01:10:46,414
[SPEAKER_00]: And, like, for example, he said $1,000 to clear cut a lot.

761
01:10:46,434 --> 01:10:46,594
[SPEAKER_00]: That's

762
01:10:48,898 --> 01:10:49,418
[SPEAKER_00]: Ridiculous.

763
01:10:49,878 --> 01:11:04,264
[SPEAKER_00]: But if it said $50,000 to clear most of the trees from a lot or all the trees smaller than 30 dbh, that might actually be something that would be worth considering.

764
01:11:04,725 --> 01:11:12,368
[SPEAKER_00]: And if it was clear-cut enough that a contractor could pay the amount and get the permit and move,

765
01:11:13,188 --> 01:11:18,931
[SPEAKER_00]: And then we might actually end up with a lot of money for trees that might in fact be worth it to us.

766
01:11:19,512 --> 01:11:35,181
[SPEAKER_00]: And he was looking for ways also that if you had a single family house that was trying to do some work and trying to add an addition or whatever, that there was a way that he could do some math and just issue it in a way that would

767
01:11:36,662 --> 01:11:49,925
[SPEAKER_00]: make people think twice, not make them just randomly do it because they wanted to do it, but would also not tie them up for months over something that maybe they were then permitted to do or something.

768
01:11:50,305 --> 01:11:56,527
[SPEAKER_00]: And so just having that conceptually that having some way of it being transactional at some level.

769
01:11:58,249 --> 01:11:59,629
[SPEAKER_00]: was what he was looking for.

770
01:11:59,649 --> 01:12:07,714
[SPEAKER_00]: So I just wanted to sort of put that conceptually as an idea that we need to work out the details to make it work.

771
01:12:08,115 --> 01:12:14,999
[SPEAKER_00]: But if there is some way where you can say at this dollar amount for this amount of stuff, it makes sense.

772
01:12:16,555 --> 01:12:34,880
[SPEAKER_00]: And I just want to also make sure you're aware that there is a process called site plan review, which is the point at which we look at a developer's project and the community development board thinks about the layout and the circulation and the everything and

773
01:12:37,141 --> 01:12:53,682
[SPEAKER_00]: If it is illegal to cut down any trees before the building permit is issued, then they're still there for the CD board to take into account and make them, keep them as part of it and help work it through.

774
01:12:54,783 --> 01:13:02,866
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's something that we do see happen, is that somebody clear cuts a lot before they come in front of any board or commission because they can.

775
01:13:03,486 --> 01:13:13,529
[SPEAKER_00]: And so it may be that they are allowed to clear cut the lot in order to build the building in the end, but they're not allowed to do it until they have all of their permits.

776
01:13:14,673 --> 01:13:23,359
[SPEAKER_00]: And at the very least, what you've just done is you've probably kept that benefit for the environment for another year or two, or maybe three.

777
01:13:23,859 --> 01:13:30,203
[SPEAKER_00]: We have, you know, we actually have some things that have been talking about coming to site plan review for years.

778
01:13:30,803 --> 01:13:37,449
[SPEAKER_00]: And we have others that have come for site plan review, gotten some levels of permits, but they don't actually have a building permit yet.

779
01:13:38,610 --> 01:13:48,338
[SPEAKER_00]: And so for them to not be allowed to cut down their trees until they're actually ready to start construction, it would help.

780
01:13:48,398 --> 01:13:54,083
[SPEAKER_00]: It doesn't solve the end problem, but it's better than them cutting them at the very beginning.

781
01:13:54,103 --> 01:13:56,866
[SPEAKER_00]: And I just wanted to, in a big picture way,

782
01:13:57,993 --> 01:13:59,476
[SPEAKER_00]: give you those thoughts as well.

783
01:13:59,877 --> 01:14:02,382
[SPEAKER_00]: My office has also been asked to submit comments.

784
01:14:04,005 --> 01:14:07,091
[SPEAKER_00]: And I would rather work with your version than

785
01:14:09,786 --> 01:14:11,648
[SPEAKER_00]: for me to go back to the council.

786
01:14:11,968 --> 01:14:17,613
[SPEAKER_00]: Like I don't want to publicly go to the city council meeting and say, I completely disagree with everything the building commissioner has said.

787
01:14:18,193 --> 01:14:19,714
[SPEAKER_00]: I would say that to them privately.

788
01:14:19,734 --> 01:14:22,176
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't want to embarrass a colleague like that, right?

789
01:14:22,257 --> 01:14:27,921
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't want him to go to a council meeting and say, I disagree with everything the director of planning and sustainability says.

790
01:14:28,602 --> 01:14:31,144
[SPEAKER_00]: So how do we sort of manage that?

791
01:14:31,284 --> 01:14:35,788
[SPEAKER_00]: And granted, this is a public meeting too, and I just said it, but it's different, right?

792
01:14:37,014 --> 01:14:38,495
[SPEAKER_02]: Very difficult, yeah.

793
01:14:39,895 --> 01:14:53,699
[SPEAKER_11]: I just want to remind folks that one of the big differences between that whole process, that whole process, I feel like we've got some support from at least the current building commissioner to work with us on this.

794
01:14:53,719 --> 01:14:55,019
[SPEAKER_11]: It sounds like from his draft.

795
01:14:55,419 --> 01:15:00,501
[SPEAKER_11]: But the other element of this is private trees where no construction is taking place.

796
01:15:00,991 --> 01:15:05,233
[SPEAKER_11]: That is in our draft, and it's not very usual.

797
01:15:05,593 --> 01:15:12,075
[SPEAKER_11]: Most of the other cities and towns are pretty much sticking to construction.

798
01:15:12,516 --> 01:15:23,280
[SPEAKER_11]: And so I would welcome your thoughts about that, especially when you see the draft, because that is different than that, and that is

799
01:15:24,360 --> 01:15:35,728
[SPEAKER_11]: The evaluation and enforcement of that is different than using the building inspection process to go through.

800
01:15:35,768 --> 01:15:37,149
[SPEAKER_11]: And that's one of the issues.

801
01:15:38,229 --> 01:15:39,630
[SPEAKER_11]: Is there the staffing in place?

802
01:15:39,730 --> 01:15:48,196
[SPEAKER_11]: And maybe the tree committee helps with reviewing any of these private tree removals that don't involve construction.

803
01:15:48,620 --> 01:15:48,820
[SPEAKER_00]: Right.

804
01:15:48,980 --> 01:15:52,961
[SPEAKER_00]: And actually, I want to encourage you to include that because I live in North Medford.

805
01:15:53,241 --> 01:15:55,521
[SPEAKER_00]: And I'll just speak from the personal perspective.

806
01:15:56,241 --> 01:16:02,522
[SPEAKER_00]: I had a neighbor take down three large trees because she was terrified and convinced that those trees were going to fall on her house.

807
01:16:03,643 --> 01:16:11,844
[SPEAKER_00]: I am convinced that those trees had been holding up the slope that her house sits on top of.

808
01:16:12,004 --> 01:16:16,305
[SPEAKER_00]: And she hired a random tree company that was willing to come cut down those trees.

809
01:16:17,305 --> 01:16:22,168
[SPEAKER_00]: And my gut, but I'm not an arborist, I don't know my gut, is it was a bad move.

810
01:16:22,488 --> 01:16:29,313
[SPEAKER_00]: But she is older than my parents, right?

811
01:16:29,393 --> 01:16:31,234
[SPEAKER_00]: She's definitely in her 80s.

812
01:16:32,015 --> 01:16:33,396
[SPEAKER_00]: And she was just nervous.

813
01:16:33,456 --> 01:16:35,377
[SPEAKER_00]: And it's not even leaves, they were pine trees.

814
01:16:36,541 --> 01:16:40,803
[SPEAKER_00]: And there was just no convincing her from, you know, that that was not an issue.

815
01:16:41,383 --> 01:16:47,766
[SPEAKER_00]: I will say, though, that my other neighbor cut down a large tree recently, and I was kind of horrified.

816
01:16:48,307 --> 01:17:01,133
[SPEAKER_00]: And she spent 40 minutes afterwards explaining to me how she hated to do it, but the arborist who came from the tree company to prune it told her that the tree really needed to come down, that it was,

817
01:17:03,003 --> 01:17:04,464
[SPEAKER_00]: It was sick and it was rotted.

818
01:17:04,864 --> 01:17:11,069
[SPEAKER_00]: And honestly, I never had the heart to go over and look at the pieces myself and know if they were lying to her or not.

819
01:17:12,530 --> 01:17:15,132
[SPEAKER_00]: But she was really unhappy about cutting down that tree.

820
01:17:15,512 --> 01:17:17,934
[SPEAKER_00]: But right again, it's the private company.

821
01:17:17,954 --> 01:17:24,599
[SPEAKER_00]: And is it the private company that you trust or is it a private company that makes its profit on tree removal?

822
01:17:25,079 --> 01:17:25,861
[SPEAKER_11]: Well, that's it.

823
01:17:25,981 --> 01:17:29,807
[SPEAKER_11]: I keep seeing different removal, tree companies around.

824
01:17:29,867 --> 01:17:32,351
[SPEAKER_11]: I mean, they're not even tree companies, they're like landscape companies.

825
01:17:32,652 --> 01:17:36,158
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm not even sure they're very good at taking trees down or anything.

826
01:17:36,383 --> 01:17:38,804
[SPEAKER_11]: I mean, it's just so random, it's so uncontrolled.

827
01:17:39,064 --> 01:17:45,285
[SPEAKER_11]: There's so many of them, I feel like I want to go around and take pictures of all of their names and numbers, but the fact is there's so many of them.

828
01:17:45,385 --> 01:17:59,149
[SPEAKER_11]: I mean, I see new names every day of companies and they have no, there is nobody on their staff that knows enough about trees to really know what's a valuable tree and what's not a valuable tree.

829
01:17:59,169 --> 01:18:02,990
