923
01:28:06,931 --> 01:28:15,155
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's just going to the mayor for signature and it will be in effect starting July 1st of next year.

924
01:28:21,839 --> 01:28:31,207
[SPEAKER_01]: The EV charging station at Roberts Elementary is already up and running, so people can use that outside of school hours.

925
01:28:31,628 --> 01:28:35,571
[SPEAKER_01]: We're still working on the other ones that are in process.

926
01:28:36,692 --> 01:28:38,134
[SPEAKER_01]: I think most of them will be

927
01:28:40,042 --> 01:28:48,987
[SPEAKER_01]: available by the end of this year, although I think the ones at the DPW and at the police station will probably be, it will probably be next year.

928
01:28:50,027 --> 01:28:58,591
[SPEAKER_01]: There were some changes around that because they will be used for fleet, at least primarily for DPW and completely for the police department.

929
01:28:58,611 --> 01:29:01,733
[SPEAKER_01]: So there were some changes around where those were going to be located.

930
01:29:05,615 --> 01:29:26,322
[SPEAKER_01]: The Climate Equity Council's first meeting was last Monday, and that was basically a level setting meeting where it was sharing a lot of information about the Climate Action Plan, getting some ideas of what areas the Council wants to focus on.

931
01:29:28,420 --> 01:29:47,607
[SPEAKER_01]: And so for the next meeting, which will be the third Monday of the month moving forward, they'll be voting on a chair, and we'll be talking about some issues like flooding, mass save incentives, and emergency shelters.

932
01:29:47,827 --> 01:29:53,509
[SPEAKER_01]: Those are things that they had identified as things that they were very much interested in.

933
01:29:54,517 --> 01:29:59,444
[SPEAKER_01]: And I know members of this committee attended that as guests.

934
01:30:00,345 --> 01:30:04,391
[SPEAKER_01]: Did you have any feedback from that meeting that you wanted to share?

935
01:30:04,411 --> 01:30:06,634
[SPEAKER_14]: I thought it was great.

936
01:30:07,515 --> 01:30:08,557
[SPEAKER_14]: Lois and I attended.

937
01:30:08,857 --> 01:30:10,840
[SPEAKER_14]: I think Barry was there for some of it.

938
01:30:12,883 --> 01:30:13,863
[SPEAKER_14]: I really thought it was great.

939
01:30:14,263 --> 01:30:19,325
[SPEAKER_14]: And they brought up concerns that I actually have, you know, like the emergency shelters.

940
01:30:19,825 --> 01:30:23,226
[SPEAKER_14]: That has been something that we've talked about for years.

941
01:30:23,667 --> 01:30:28,648
[SPEAKER_14]: You know, if we have no, we go to electrification, you don't have electricity, where do we go?

942
01:30:28,668 --> 01:30:31,369
[SPEAKER_14]: We have no heat, you know, so we really,

943
01:30:33,551 --> 01:30:36,973
[SPEAKER_14]: need an emergency shelter to go to.

944
01:30:37,734 --> 01:30:39,715
[SPEAKER_14]: And I was curious about a couple of things.

945
01:30:40,175 --> 01:30:46,239
[SPEAKER_14]: There were certain groups I didn't see represented in there, but maybe they weren't at the meeting.

946
01:30:47,000 --> 01:30:48,261
[SPEAKER_14]: And I was wondering about seniors.

947
01:30:49,081 --> 01:30:51,022
[SPEAKER_14]: Are seniors part of that group?

948
01:30:53,424 --> 01:30:56,886
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't think there are any seniors that are part of that group currently.

949
01:30:57,487 --> 01:31:02,730
[SPEAKER_01]: Right now, when we started that council, it was really focused on

950
01:31:03,450 --> 01:31:10,852
[SPEAKER_01]: groups that have been underrepresented and a lot of the feedback that the city has received around the Climate Action Plan.

951
01:31:11,373 --> 01:31:26,778
[SPEAKER_01]: And so there's a lot of focus, there's been a lot of focus on getting feedback from, you know, folks who speak languages other than English as their primary language, people of color,

952
01:31:27,958 --> 01:31:34,222
[SPEAKER_01]: folks who we haven't necessarily had as much participation from in the past.

953
01:31:34,382 --> 01:31:46,449
[SPEAKER_01]: Although this is just the first group, I know moving forward as people, you know, as people leave the committee and new people come on, there might be others that are included as part of that.

954
01:31:48,034 --> 01:31:49,495
[SPEAKER_14]: I'd like to recommend that group.

955
01:31:50,336 --> 01:31:59,962
[SPEAKER_14]: I meet a lot of seniors and we've seen a lot of seniors reach out to us that really have no clue and they need assistance or advice or want input.

956
01:32:01,824 --> 01:32:11,831
[SPEAKER_14]: That's a large majority of homeowners and renters here that just need that extra group participation and to know what's available.

957
01:32:12,771 --> 01:32:13,052
[SPEAKER_14]: Maybe.

958
01:32:13,072 --> 01:32:13,232
[SPEAKER_14]: Yeah.

959
01:32:13,967 --> 01:32:15,548
[SPEAKER_14]: isn't it, maybe this isn't it.

960
01:32:16,028 --> 01:32:21,550
[SPEAKER_14]: And the other group, I didn't see, ethnic-wise, I'll just say Asian influence?

961
01:32:25,051 --> 01:32:39,676
[SPEAKER_01]: I believe we do have a person who speaks Mandarin as part of the, that might be the liaisons, actually, and not the connectors that I'm thinking of right now, but that's the point.

962
01:32:40,756 --> 01:32:42,577
[SPEAKER_14]: Is it two different groups?

963
01:32:43,440 --> 01:32:56,727
[SPEAKER_01]: There are some groups that are, there's a group that's a part-time city employees who help people more with public health related things like signing people up for mass health and things like that.

964
01:32:58,568 --> 01:33:01,750
[SPEAKER_01]: There's some community liaisons, I think is what they're called.

965
01:33:06,378 --> 01:33:19,850
[SPEAKER_01]: But if you do hear people who are, you know, have questions and who, about the sorts of things that we're talking about there, especially like Mass Save and things like that, definitely please bring that to our attention.

966
01:33:19,890 --> 01:33:23,693
[SPEAKER_01]: I would hope that anybody in this group who does would do that too.

967
01:33:30,036 --> 01:33:42,682
[SPEAKER_01]: Speaking of emergency shelters, though, I wanted to mention that we are working on a project at the Andrews School where we'll be doing some rewiring to put additional things on the emergency circuit.

968
01:33:43,202 --> 01:33:48,064
[SPEAKER_01]: So there's currently a backup generator there, and this would be putting things onto that emergency circuit.

969
01:33:48,665 --> 01:33:55,688
[SPEAKER_01]: So in addition to some rewiring that will happen with some HVAC electrification that we're hoping to do,

970
01:33:56,344 --> 01:34:01,985
[SPEAKER_01]: in the near future, that that school will be able to be used as an emergency shelter.

971
01:34:05,246 --> 01:34:20,549
[SPEAKER_14]: You know, it's interesting, in the, I don't know, in the past, I'm going to say old days, but it used to be that all schools, you know, in the 50s and 60s, 70s and whatever, were considered emergency shelters.

972
01:34:22,550 --> 01:34:22,930
[SPEAKER_14]: Is that,

973
01:34:24,326 --> 01:34:26,227
[SPEAKER_14]: Something talks about it.

974
01:34:27,688 --> 01:34:29,429
[SPEAKER_14]: There were emergencies.

975
01:34:29,809 --> 01:34:40,594
[SPEAKER_14]: And you know, and I had them in the electricity and the water and you know, some of them had back up food that they would rotate every year is still something that exists.

976
01:34:42,210 --> 01:34:47,593
[SPEAKER_01]: There might be a different focus because it was so much focused on bomb shelter.

977
01:34:47,613 --> 01:34:59,379
[SPEAKER_01]: We're more focused right now, I think, on emergency, on extreme weather type of things where people might lose power or they might not have heat to their homes.

978
01:34:59,439 --> 01:35:01,240
[SPEAKER_09]: I'd like to point out that

979
01:35:02,653 --> 01:35:19,346
[SPEAKER_09]: This is not to minimize the need for emergency shelter when when there's a loss for power but that electrification doesn't make a difference and that because fossil fuel heated homes also depend on electrical systems in order to work.

980
01:35:20,007 --> 01:35:23,550
[SPEAKER_09]: So when your electricity is out you have oil like I do.

981
01:35:24,978 --> 01:35:25,698
[SPEAKER_09]: your heat is out.

982
01:35:27,560 --> 01:35:40,671
[SPEAKER_09]: And in fact, as we go through electrification and homes are better insulated and weatherized, the need will probably be slightly less, but still there.

983
01:35:41,872 --> 01:35:51,720
[SPEAKER_01]: People will be able to stay in their homes for longer because they won't lose the heat quite so quickly if they have a better envelope.

984
01:35:51,740 --> 01:35:52,280
[SPEAKER_01]: Definitely.

985
01:35:52,300 --> 01:35:52,701
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

986
01:35:54,300 --> 01:36:02,963
[SPEAKER_14]: I just threw that out there, Brenda, because I was curious if the old shelters are still in existence and can also be used for consideration.

987
01:36:03,023 --> 01:36:04,843
[SPEAKER_14]: Most people don't know.

988
01:36:04,863 --> 01:36:05,743
[SPEAKER_01]: That's a good question.

989
01:36:05,883 --> 01:36:06,204
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know.

990
01:36:06,244 --> 01:36:07,044
[SPEAKER_01]: I should look into that.

991
01:36:07,104 --> 01:36:07,324
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

992
01:36:07,404 --> 01:36:11,105
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know.

993
01:36:11,385 --> 01:36:15,526
[SPEAKER_01]: So also with the Andrews School, we're looking to add solar to the roof.

994
01:36:16,527 --> 01:36:17,807
[SPEAKER_01]: And so that's something that we are

995
01:36:18,711 --> 01:36:31,282
[SPEAKER_01]: Working on getting at least a letter of intent done by the end of this year so that we can file for some for smart incentives before they change at the end of this year for that project.

996
01:36:34,105 --> 01:36:44,334
[SPEAKER_01]: We're also working on a school bus electrification plan so the state has some free technical assistance for municipalities to develop plans.

997
01:36:44,970 --> 01:36:50,312
[SPEAKER_01]: And so it's basically looking at, you know, multiple options that would be available to us.

998
01:36:50,352 --> 01:37:04,618
[SPEAKER_01]: So we're working with the Met for Public Schools to look at ownership options, lease options, everything across the board so that a decision could be made about how that could be done.

999
01:37:07,295 --> 01:37:20,883
[SPEAKER_01]: And there's a lot of federal funding available for that and state funding for, you know, once we get past this technical assistance phase to actually purchasing the buses, although they are a lot more expensive than regular buses, so that's needed.

1000
01:37:25,105 --> 01:37:30,168
[SPEAKER_01]: And we submitted our Green Communities Annual Report last week.

1001
01:37:32,029 --> 01:37:32,530
[SPEAKER_01]: Bye, Alicia.

1002
01:37:32,570 --> 01:37:33,230
[SPEAKER_01]: Thanks for joining.

1003
01:37:37,130 --> 01:37:39,472
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, we submit our green communities annual report last week.

1004
01:37:40,092 --> 01:37:40,773
[SPEAKER_01]: It looks pretty good.

1005
01:37:40,813 --> 01:37:42,394
[SPEAKER_01]: It looks like weather normalized.

1006
01:37:43,294 --> 01:37:48,198
[SPEAKER_01]: We are energy use has dropped from for municipal buildings has dropped.

1007
01:37:48,678 --> 01:37:53,321
[SPEAKER_01]: I think 15% roughly since 2009.

1008
01:37:54,622 --> 01:37:56,483
[SPEAKER_01]: So definitely could be doing better.

1009
01:37:56,623 --> 01:38:02,247
[SPEAKER_01]: But it's a it's a drop from last year as well so I think that's a good sign.

1010
01:38:03,848 --> 01:38:04,949
[SPEAKER_01]: Always do want to do more.

1011
01:38:08,419 --> 01:38:23,093
[SPEAKER_01]: And then, Bob, you asked for sort of a summary of the state's climate chief's recommendations that came out last month.

1012
01:38:23,294 --> 01:38:31,442
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's really very broad, a lot of different things across the entire state.

1013
01:38:32,983 --> 01:38:35,805
[SPEAKER_01]: the entire state programs.

1014
01:38:36,385 --> 01:38:51,755
[SPEAKER_01]: So this is really looking at sort of like a whole government approach to climate change action and really trying to just like break down silos across all of these different departments.

1015
01:38:53,136 --> 01:39:01,721
[SPEAKER_01]: One of the things that talked about was a new federal funds and infrastructure office was created and they have proposed

1016
01:39:02,681 --> 01:39:17,348
[SPEAKER_01]: a capital investment in debt reduction fund, which is $750 million in state matching funds for municipalities that are applying for federal grants, which is really important.

1017
01:39:17,648 --> 01:39:26,252
[SPEAKER_01]: So if Medford is applying for federal funding, there are matching requirements for that, and it can be hard for the city to come up with that match.

1018
01:39:26,312 --> 01:39:28,132
[SPEAKER_01]: So something like this would really help.

1019
01:39:28,212 --> 01:39:30,473
[SPEAKER_01]: And this has been proposed to the legislature.

1020
01:39:32,181 --> 01:39:37,103
[SPEAKER_01]: but that hasn't been approved yet, but that would really be very welcome from our perspective.

1021
01:39:40,884 --> 01:39:47,466
[SPEAKER_01]: They talk a lot about different, you know, funding options, capital investment changes, things like that.

1022
01:39:47,506 --> 01:39:52,108
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm trying to highlight a few things that I think you'd be particularly interested in.

1023
01:39:54,388 --> 01:39:56,109
[SPEAKER_01]: They're looking to incorporate

1024
01:39:56,923 --> 01:40:03,388
[SPEAKER_01]: the CECP and resilience mandates into municipal grants.

1025
01:40:03,448 --> 01:40:15,656
[SPEAKER_01]: So those are like the carbon emission, the greenhouse gas emissions goals and the resilience goals into municipal grants moving forward.

1026
01:40:15,737 --> 01:40:24,403
[SPEAKER_01]: So that'll be really important for us to keep an eye on for any sort of like capital projects that we're doing that we're getting state grants for.

1027
01:40:24,443 --> 01:40:25,744
[SPEAKER_01]: We'll need to make sure that

1028
01:40:27,829 --> 01:40:30,852
[SPEAKER_01]: We're incorporating these goals into them as well.

1029
01:40:33,795 --> 01:40:46,128
[SPEAKER_01]: It recommends strengthening the MIPA forest clearing reviews and developing MIPA EJ, environmental justice guidance on urban tree canopy.

1030
01:40:47,082 --> 01:40:51,845
[SPEAKER_01]: and incorporating the social cost of greenhouse gases into environmental reviews for MEPA.

1031
01:40:53,966 --> 01:40:58,989
[SPEAKER_01]: So I don't know if that's going to affect Medford directly.

1032
01:40:59,069 --> 01:41:04,413
[SPEAKER_01]: Maybe the urban tree canopy guidance would be something that we could look into once that gets developed.

1033
01:41:07,775 --> 01:41:10,856
[SPEAKER_01]: They are looking to increase funding to MassCEC.

1034
01:41:12,182 --> 01:41:14,284
[SPEAKER_01]: which would be amazing.

1035
01:41:14,925 --> 01:41:20,872
[SPEAKER_01]: They provide lots of grants for a whole host of clean energy projects.

1036
01:41:24,676 --> 01:41:31,023
[SPEAKER_01]: They want to analyze what the best use would be for mass save funding.

1037
01:41:32,785 --> 01:41:43,233
[SPEAKER_01]: whether that is a utility run program or if it's something else entirely, and establishing a decarbonization clearinghouse by 2024.

1038
01:41:45,175 --> 01:41:59,547
[SPEAKER_01]: And so, you know, sort of a central place that's pointing out to all the programs as sort of a first step to, is there going to be some sort of transformation to the Mass Save program into something that's really more focused on a total decarbonization?

1039
01:42:01,893 --> 01:42:04,974
[SPEAKER_01]: focus rather than just energy efficiency.

1040
01:42:09,216 --> 01:42:29,903
[SPEAKER_01]: Another thing that they talk about is MSBA, the school funding source, Municipal School Building Association, I think that's what it stands for, requiring that they fund only all electric school buildings moving forward.

1041
01:42:30,787 --> 01:42:36,010
[SPEAKER_01]: and that they incentivize net zero and resilient buildings.

1042
01:42:37,391 --> 01:42:45,795
[SPEAKER_01]: And they're already incentivizing, you know, improvements over sort of the baseline right now, but this would be taking it a step farther.

1043
01:42:49,317 --> 01:42:56,701
[SPEAKER_01]: And then it talks about public health, mostly really focusing on data and planning around that.

1044
01:42:59,144 --> 01:43:10,072
[SPEAKER_01]: workforce, including a Climate Service Corps, curriculum changes, and economic development plans.

1045
01:43:10,172 --> 01:43:16,096
[SPEAKER_01]: So there's a lot of things saying we need a plan for this and then to implement whatever that plan is.

1046
01:43:18,298 --> 01:43:23,381
[SPEAKER_01]: So, but I think it's all, you know, really good next steps, definitely.

1047
01:43:23,421 --> 01:43:28,065
[SPEAKER_01]: And some of these specificities that are in the report are really helpful.

1048
01:43:30,074 --> 01:43:32,355
[SPEAKER_01]: or will be if they actually get accomplished.

1049
01:43:35,897 --> 01:43:49,285
[SPEAKER_01]: And then I think, Bob, you also asked for an update on the clean heat platform that Green Energy Consumers Alliance is sending around for comments to legislators.

1050
01:43:54,529 --> 01:44:22,023
[SPEAKER_01]: Its main areas are focusing around an equitable transition away from fossil fuels, focusing a lot of funding on low and moderate income households, environmental justice communities, having an equity advisory council, and putting $300 million into a fund for affordable housing and public buildings in environmental justice communities and gateway cities.

1051
01:44:23,385 --> 01:44:33,133
[SPEAKER_01]: They talk about electrification, including saying that hydrogen should not be injected into our natural gas pipelines.

1052
01:44:34,674 --> 01:44:38,177
[SPEAKER_01]: There shouldn't be subsidies for hydrogen to heat buildings.

1053
01:44:40,078 --> 01:44:48,985
[SPEAKER_01]: They want to add incentives for additional incentives for electrification and only have subsidies for biofuels if they come from waste feedstock.

1054
01:44:51,048 --> 01:44:55,891
[SPEAKER_01]: and updating Mass Save for decarbonization assessments, not just energy efficiency.

1055
01:45:00,254 --> 01:45:11,180
[SPEAKER_01]: They talk about moving beyond gas, so removing the cap on the fossil fuel demonstration project, which is currently only 10 cities that can participate, and opening that up to more cities.

1056
01:45:12,901 --> 01:45:16,844
[SPEAKER_01]: Requiring gas companies to make annual plans

1057
01:45:18,064 --> 01:45:24,429
[SPEAKER_01]: to meet the greenhouse gas mandates, including electrification and pipeline retirement.

1058
01:45:25,689 --> 01:45:36,877
[SPEAKER_01]: Allowing gas companies to sell thermal energy, so geothermal projects like Eversource is doing as a demonstration project right now.

1059
01:45:38,558 --> 01:45:44,582
[SPEAKER_01]: No gas pipeline expansion and no cost recovery for gas pipelines after 2050.

1060
01:45:47,753 --> 01:45:52,356
[SPEAKER_01]: and no new large fossil fuel projects.

1061
01:45:53,937 --> 01:45:56,918
[SPEAKER_01]: It talks about a performance standard for large buildings.

1062
01:45:57,879 --> 01:46:00,641
[SPEAKER_01]: And so that's 20,000 square feet and up.

1063
01:46:01,921 --> 01:46:07,424
[SPEAKER_01]: So they would have to report their emissions and stay below certain emission standards.

1064
01:46:09,486 --> 01:46:17,170
[SPEAKER_01]: And then updating existing programs like green communities to go further than it goes right now.

1065
01:46:17,967 --> 01:46:32,297
[SPEAKER_01]: Repealing the alternative portfolio standard and replacing it with a clean heat standard, which has credits for electric systems and reporting for heating fuel suppliers.

1066
01:46:34,479 --> 01:46:46,347
[SPEAKER_01]: And then moving the solar ready mandate from the specialized code into the stretch code so that it would apply to more communities without them adopting the specialized code.

1067
01:46:48,802 --> 01:46:52,464
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think that that's the majority of it.

1068
01:46:52,825 --> 01:46:58,669
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, I think they're summarizing a lot of what people have been saying for a long time.

1069
01:46:58,689 --> 01:47:04,913
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't see anything in there that's particularly alarming.

1070
01:47:05,613 --> 01:47:09,676
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm pretty much in agreement myself with everything that they list there.

1071
01:47:11,237 --> 01:47:13,919
[SPEAKER_01]: So it's definitely a good thing.

1072
01:47:15,213 --> 01:47:19,215
[SPEAKER_01]: focus, I think, for a lot of the advocacy that's happening around this.

1073
01:47:21,756 --> 01:47:23,196
[SPEAKER_07]: Thanks for that summary.

1074
01:47:26,358 --> 01:47:37,483
[SPEAKER_07]: Maybe you mentioned this, the grant that you were talking about, the $300,000 grant or $150,000 grant, what's the status of that again?

1075
01:47:39,443 --> 01:47:42,985
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, for the electrification, the Electrify Medford campaign.

1076
01:47:43,587 --> 01:47:45,108
[SPEAKER_01]: I haven't heard back about that.

1077
01:47:47,088 --> 01:47:55,051
[SPEAKER_01]: We received some questions before Thanksgiving on the application, and we responded to them.

1078
01:47:55,311 --> 01:47:57,952
[SPEAKER_01]: So we're still waiting for the final decision there.

1079
01:47:57,972 --> 01:48:01,654
[SPEAKER_07]: When do you think, will we know that by the next meeting?

1080
01:48:03,414 --> 01:48:03,815
[SPEAKER_01]: We should.

1081
01:48:03,855 --> 01:48:06,095
[SPEAKER_01]: They said December is when we could expect it.

1082
01:48:06,355 --> 01:48:06,596
[SPEAKER_07]: Great.

1083
01:48:06,716 --> 01:48:06,976
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

1084
01:48:06,996 --> 01:48:08,316
[SPEAKER_07]: We'll cross our fingers.

1085
01:48:11,998 --> 01:48:13,078
[SPEAKER_07]: Is that it?

1086
01:48:15,184 --> 01:48:18,707
[SPEAKER_01]: That's all that I have, unless anybody has any questions about any of it.

1087
01:48:19,687 --> 01:48:31,295
[SPEAKER_07]: We're getting to our last five minutes, so we can talk about obviously 2024 initiatives in our next meeting, if we have time.

1088
01:48:33,776 --> 01:48:42,142
[SPEAKER_07]: But Brenda, you're leading the charge in many of these areas, and if we get this grant for electrification, that'll be a key component, I think.

1089
01:48:44,162 --> 01:48:52,708
[SPEAKER_13]: It's really encouraging to hear how long that list of things you talked about was, how full it was.

1090
01:48:54,589 --> 01:49:01,254
[SPEAKER_13]: When I first started with this kind of stuff, it was one thing here, one thing there.

1091
01:49:02,835 --> 01:49:07,578
[SPEAKER_13]: It's comforting to hear how many things are being talked about.

1092
01:49:10,794 --> 01:49:14,116
[SPEAKER_05]: definitely very busy right now, and it's just going to pick up.

1093
01:49:14,136 --> 01:49:20,480
[SPEAKER_07]: All right, well, good.

